**Version Used**: 
VS 2022 v17.1.0 Preview 2.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Add the following class:
```cs
#nullable enable

public class Foo
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    public static bool operator ==(Foo? left, Foo? right)
    {
        // When ReferenceEquals returns false, left and right cannot both be null.
        if (ReferenceEquals(left, right))
        {
            return true;
        }

        // When ReferenceEquals returns false, neither left nor right can be null.
        if (ReferenceEquals(left, null))
        {
            return false;
        }

        return left.Id == right.Id;
    }

    public static bool operator !=(Foo? left, Foo? right)
    {
        return !(left == right);
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

In the equality operator of **Foo**, I would expect no CS8602 for invoking the **Id** property on the `right` argument as it has been proven not to be **null** by the two `Object.ReferenceEquals` calls.

**Actual Behavior**:

```txt
Foo.cs(21,27,21,32): warning CS8602: Dereference of a possibly null reference
```

